To add Mailtrap to your Spring Boot application, you can follow these steps:

Step 1: Add the Mailtrap dependency to your pom.xml file:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.mailtrap</groupId>
    <artifactId>mailtrap-spring-boot-starter</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0</version>
</dependency>
```

Step 2: Configure Mailtrap in your application.properties file:

```properties
spring.mail.host=smtp.mailtrap.io
spring.mail.port=587
spring.mail.username=your-mailtrap-username
spring.mail.password=your-mailtrap-password
```

Replace "your-mailtrap-username" and "your-mailtrap-password" with your actual Mailtrap credentials.

Step 3: Use the MailtrapSender in your code:

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.mail.SimpleMailMessage;
import org.springframework.mail.javamail.JavaMailSender;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class MailService {

    @Autowired
    private JavaMailSender mailSender;

    public void sendEmail(String to, String subject, String body) {
        SimpleMailMessage message = new SimpleMailMessage();
        message.setTo(to);
        message.setSubject(subject);
        message.setText(body);
        mailSender.send(message);
    }
}
```

This is a simple example of a service class that uses the MailtrapSender to send an email.

You can now use the `MailService` class to send emails in your application.

